== Literature ==

=== Marathi ===

The Yadavas were the first major dynasty to use Marathi as an official language.{{sfn|Cynthia Talbot|2001|p=211}} Earlier, both Sanskrit and Kannada had been used in present-day Maharashtra; subsequently, at least partly due to the efforts of the Yadava rulers, Marathi became the dominant language of the region.{{sfn|Cynthia Talbot|2001|p=212}} Even if they were not of Marathi origin, towards the end of their reign, they certainly identified with the Marathi language.{{sfn|Christian Lee Novetzke|2016|p=316}} The early Marathi literature emerged during the Yadava rule, because of which some scholars have theorized that it was produced with support from the Yadava rulers.{{sfn|Christian Lee Novetzke|2016|p=74,86}} However, there is no evidence that the Yadava royal court directly supported the production of Marathi literature with state funds, although it regarded Marathi as a significant language for connecting with the general public.{{sfn|Christian Lee Novetzke|2016|p=x,74}}

[[Hemadri]], a minister in the Yadava court, attempted to formalize Marathi with Sanskrit expressions to boost its status as a court language.{{sfn|Cynthia Talbot|2001|pp=211-212}} Saint-poet [[Dnyaneshwar]] wrote ''[[Dnyaneshwari]]'' (c. 1290), a Marathi-language commentary on the ''[[Bhagavad Gita]]'', during Ramachandra's rule. He also composed devotional songs called ''abhanga''s. Dnyaneshwar gave a higher status to Marathi by translating the sacred [[Bhagavad Gita|Geeta]] from [[Sanskrit]]. Mukundaraja wrote the Marathi-language philosophical treatises ''Paramamrita'' and ''Vivekasindhu'' during the Yadava period.{{sfn|Onkar Prasad Verma|1970|p=266}} The [[Mahanubhava]] religious sect, which became prominent in present-day Maharshtra during the late Yadava period, boosted the status of Marathi as a literary language.{{sfn|Onkar Prasad Verma|1970|p=266}} Mahimabhatta wrote ''Lilacharita'', a biography of the sect's founder [[Chakradhara]]. The text claims that Hemadri (who was a [[Brahmanism|Brahmanist]]) was jealous of Chakradhara's popularity, and the Yadava king Ramachandra ordered killing of Chakradhara, who escaped with his yogic powers. The claim is of doubtful historicity.{{sfn|A. V. Narasimha Murthy|1971|p=32}}

=== Kannada ===

Kannada was one of the court languages during early Seuna times, as is evident from a number of Kannada-language inscriptions (see [[#Origin|Origin]] section). Kamalabhava, patronised by Bhillama V, wrote ''Santhishwarapurana''. Achanna composed ''Varadhamanapurana'' in 1198. Amugideva, patronised by Simhana II, composed many ''[[Vachanas]]'' or devotional songs. Chaundarasa of [[Pandharapur]] wrote ''Dashakumara Charite'' around 1300.<ref name="kamala1">R. Narasimhacharya, p. 68, ''History of Kannada Literature'', 1988, Asian Educational Services, New Delhi, Madras, 1988 {{ISBN|81-206-0303-6}}</ref>{{sfn|Suryanath Kamat|1980|pp=143-144}}<ref name="sujit">Sujit Mukherjee, p. 410, p. 247, "Dictionary of Indian Literature One: Beginnings - 1850", 1999, Orient Blackswan, Delhi, {{ISBN|81 250 1453 5}}</ref>

[[Simhana]] patronized [[Changdev Maharaj|Changadeva]] and the Kannada poet Kamalabhava.

=== Sanskrit ===

[[Simhana]] was a great patron of learning and literature. He established the college of astronomy to study the work of celebrated astronomer [[Bhaskaracharya]]. The [[Sangita Ratnakara]], an authoritative [[Sanskrit]] work on [[Music of India|Indian music]] was written by [[Sharngadeva|Śārṅgadeva]] (or Shrangadeva) during Simhana's reign.<ref name="GSMann">{{cite book |author=Gurinder Singh Mann | title = The Making of Sikh Scripture |year=2001 |publisher = Oxford University Press US |isbn = 0-19-513024-3 |page = 1 }}</ref>

[[Hemadri]] compiled the encyclopedic Sanskrit work ''Chaturvarga Chintamani''. He is said to have built many temples in a style known after him – ''Hemadapanti''.<ref name="palkhi">{{cite book |author=Digambar Balkrishna Mokashi | title = Palkhi: An Indian Pilgrimage |year=1987 | publisher = SUNY Press | isbn = 0-88706-461-2 | page = 37 }}</ref> He wrote many books on ''vaidhyakshastra'' (medical science) and he introduced and supported [[Pearl millet|bajra]] cultivation.<ref name="kolarkar">Marathyancha Itihaas by Dr. S.G Kolarkar, p.4, Shri Mangesh Prakashan, Nagpur.</ref>

Other Sanskrit literary works created during the Seuna period include:

* ''[[Suktimuktavali]]'' by Jalhana
* ''Hammiramadhana'' by Jayasimha Suri{{cn|date=March 2018}}
* ''Karnakutuhala'' and ''Siddhanta Shiromani'' by [[Bhaskaracharya]]
* Anantadeva's commentaries on [[Varahamihira]]'s ''Brijajjataka'' and [[Brahmagupta]]'s ''Brihatsputa siddhanta''
* Haripaladeva's ''Sangeetasudhakara'', a treatise on [[Indian Classical Music]], which bifurcates Indian classical music as [[Hindustani Music]] and [[Carnatic Music]] for the first time, acknowledging the [[Muslim]] influence on Indian music.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = ITCSRA FAQ on Indian Classical Music
  | url = http://www.itcsra.org/sra_faq_index.html
  | accessdate = 2007-12-11 }}</ref>{{verification failed|date=February 2018}}

